{"key":"processedPost-17077572","value":{"id":17077572,"first":17073472,"last":17079987,"when":1350910784,"utime":"10/22/12 03:59 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>Sativaman420 said:</b><br />Is it normal for there to be pooling water before you put the jars in the pressure cooker? My first time using rye grass seed, last week, I poured the excess water off before pressure cooking, and now my jars seem a tad bit on the dry side. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />Yes.&nbsp; Since we don't rinse, simmer, or boil rye grass seed the way we do with rye grain, the water doesn't fully absorb until you put it in the pressure cooker.&nbsp; It's best to mix the water and seed, and then shake well.&nbsp; Let it sit for an hour or two and shake again, and then PC.&nbsp; The hour or two of sitting is optional, but seems to help the seeds to hydrate a bit slower, avoiding damage.<br />RR","title":"Re: When preparing jars of rye grass seed...","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}